<br>
Not only does every class hold aggro differently, but every single person holds it differently. I am not ashamed to admit that I sometimes Slow earlym get aggro, and die. Although this usually only occurs when Slow is resisted.<br>
<br>
Warriors can get aggro. I great example is a wonderful halfling fellow I grouped with at crystalline golems recently in PoV. He was wielding a Greatstaff of Thunder that procced Planar Stun. Now that BoT is open to the 62+ public, this is not an expensive weapon. Planar Stun is an excellent aggro inducer.<br>
<br>
He would start swinging, I would wait a couple seconds and Tash. As soon as he saw the Tash message, he would Taunt. I would wait a couple more seconds and Slow. As soon as he saw the Slow message, he would Taunt. If I saw his weapon proc, I could get the critter slowed almost immediately. And he must have had a great Dex, cause he let out a Planar Stun very early most of the time.<br>
<br>
If Slow was resisted, I had Arcane Rune (self-only 1500 hp Rune) and Uproar (450 hp Rune and Str buff) up on myself for backup.<br>
<br>
This was a case where there were no problems and I could Slow very early (warrior with great proc, the dex to make it work,  and great timing).<br>
<br>
However, I've also worked with other warriors that have different styles. Some warriors have defensive AAs, tons of HP, weapons with less aggro, and time Taunts differently. For these warriors, they prefer to stand in there unslowed for several seconds. Sometimes I need to wait for these warriors to get near 50% health before I throw in Tash/Slow.<br>
<br>
Sometimes there's a fine line between Slowing too early (and the Slower dies) or Slowing too late (and the main tank dies).<br>
<br>
Anyway, my point is that aggro can take time to figure out when you're in a pickup group. But I will always be as aggressive as I can with Slows to try and maximize my group's potential. And I will always push a little in the first several pulls, to see just how fast I can get away with Slowing with a tank I've never hunted with.<br>
<br>
Fnortner Maguffin<br>
65th Gnomish Enchanter<br>
Lux Aeternam <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jebbar>Jebbar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 284<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/13/03 3:31 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4888.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: You are not doing your tanks job better than him or her.</span><hr size=1> I will have to tentatively agree with most of the posters here--if you're pulling agro, you need to learn to manage your agro better. I see a lot of KEI-addicted nukers who don't know when to start or stop. I also see necros who have solo'd their way to 60 who don't know about FD. If the tank is a warrior, you have to be careful about drawing agro, and this is a learned skill.<br>
<br>
That being said, I play a monk. I can tank passably well, but I have no spells and cannot taunt. In most exp groups I join, I am the puller. My job is to bring back a manageable number of enemies to the group in a timely manner. The tank's job is to <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>hold agro</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> and take hits. After I pull, I FD. This allows the tank to take agro from me. If I am in a group with a knight tank, I can limit the FD time to 1 sec or less, or even forego it altogether at times. If I am in a group with a warrior tank, I need to FD for a few secs after I pull. If, after that initial agro is gone, I draw agro again during the fight, I FD again for a few seconds. If I have to FD more than 3 times during a fight (not including the intial pull FD), I have determined that the warrior has crappy gear and I tank for the rest of the fight. If I have to continue this behavior, I let the group know that there is a new main tank.<br>
<br>
In a raid situation, it is worth it to stand around and let the warrior build agro. Defensive disc is what makes it worth the extra time. However, in an exp group, I and most people I know don't want to stand around waiting for the warrior to build agro before we do anything. On a raid, warrior tank is the only choice. In an exp group, whoever holds agro better (while still being able to take hits--I'm not advocating wizard tanks here) is the best choice.<br>
<br>
There are many times when the group is responsible for who has agro. However, there are also some times when you just have a warrior in crappy gear (or low level) who should not be tanking.<br>
<br>
